NAME

      sh - shell, the Standard command language shell Unix Interpreter (sh, bash, csh)

LIBRARY

      Standard C Library

SYNOPSIS

      sh - End of the first trimester to Holberton school Laval.

DESCRIPTION

      This program simulate a command interpreter based in Unix and GNU/LINUX with its basic commands, through a terminal emulator and some executable instructions (shell scripts) the user can interact with.
      This simple-shell is not supossed to be an exact imitation of the original Unix Shell.
      This doesn't cover all of the instructions the original does.
      This man page is not intended to be a tutorial nor a complete specification of the shell.

EXEMPLES

      Execute a shell command
      mkdir (Make Directory)
      Syntaxe: mkdir $\langle$dir1$\rangle$$\langle$dir2$\rangle$ ...$\langle$dirN$\rangle$
      Example: mkdir /tmp/test will create the directory test in /tmp. 

OVERVIEW

      This program is made to complete the team project in C - Simple Shell.
      cd : Change the current directory
      cp : Copy one or many files or directory
      ls : Display informations on files or directory
      mv : Move one or many files towards other files or directory
      rm : Remove file(s)
      mkdir : Make new directory
      rmdir : Remove empty directory
      man : Display the manuel for the given command
      more : Display the content of the file, one at the time
      cat : Display all the content of the file 
      echo : Display the given arguments
      grep : Display all the lines in the file corresponding to the given expression (search)


FEATURES

      This program displays a prompt and wait for the user to type a command. A command line always ends with a new line (when user push ENTER key).
      The prompt is displayed again each time a command has been executed.
      When the user enters exit, the shell will end.
      The user could stop the program using Ctrl+D (end of file).
      The shell handles command lines with arguments and pathways.
      The program prints the current enviroment when the user types env.
      This program executes the most common shell commands as ls, grep, find, pwd, rm, cp, mv, exit, env, history, etc... with arguments.
      If an executable cannot be found, It prints an error message and display the prompt again.
      The Shell does NOT support wildcard characters such as ls *.dat in parameters (or commands). 
      This shell does NOT support pipes |, shell logical operators as && or ||, neither commands separator ;.

ERRORS

      No unknow errors.


STANDARDS

      POSIX

HISTORY

      A sh command, the Thompson shell, appeared in Version 1 AT&T UNIX. It was superseded in Version 7 AT&T UNIX by the Bourne shell, which inherited the name sh.
      This  version  of  sh was rewritten in 1989 under the BSD license after the Bourne shell from AT&T System V Release 4 UNIX and  first  appeared in 4.3BSD Net/2.

BUGS

      No unknow bugs.
